node.text:
The glorious Cotswold hotel @thyme.england was founded with an ethos of caring for and celebrating the land, an ethos expressed through its beautiful gardens, botanically inspired decoration, and seasonal cooking based around locally grown (often home-grown) produce. This summer (starting June 15) Thyme is staging its first exhibition in the estate's restored Tithe Barn – a celebration of the country meadow in pressed flowers by Brixton-based @jamjar_flowers. In time for the launch of the exhibition on June 15, the JamJar team have created a charming tutorial on how to press flowers especially for House & Garden.

Film by @frederickjewson
Thanks to @long_elgar

node.title: How to press flowers with JamJar and Thyme

node.text: March is the month when seed sowing starts in earnest, and our own @clarefostergardens has been preparing hers in her garden in Berkshire. In this video from her greenhouse, she talks us through how to sow seeds, discussing the the vegetables she's sowing, like chard and beetroot, and flowers like calendula and phlox.

node.title: How to sow seeds with our garden editor Clare Foster

node.text: 'I Can't Breathe' a piece of choreography by Principal of the Royal Ballet @marcisambe created in memory of George Floyd who was murdered in Minnesota last week. Expect more from us over the coming weeks. For now we urge you to support @blklivesmatter and @blmuk, and keep the conversation about how we can change going forward.

Grounded in a respect for tradition and love of old buildings, designer @emma__ainscough has brought a refined playful spirit to her London flat, using her favourite colours and patterns throughout. In the bedroom, the headboard is covered in @bennisonuk’s 'Jungle Colors on Oyster' fabric, piped in linen by Hackney Draper. The walls are painted in 'Wedgwood Green' by @eico_paints. 'I love green - it’s made the room feel very calm. It's cool in the summer but cosy in winter.' Follow the link in our profile to see the full story.
📸 @lissiwaite

node.text:
The writer and garden-maker Umberto Pasti and his partner Stephan Janson, a French-born fashion designer and couturier, fell in love with Morocco more than 30 years ago. ‘We drove through the mountains towards Tangier and came across fields of irises as dramatic as an El Greco painting. It was raining and there was the most beautiful double rainbow.’ The gods were clearly pointing them towards Tangier, which in those days was like a ‘big village’, so they bought a house with some land not far from the city centre and Umberto began to make a garden there. He now has another house and garden in the countryside at Rohuna, both exquisite and filled with objects collected over a lifetime. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸 @minh_ngoc | @houseandgardenuk

node.text:
When Bianca Fincham and her family moved to Cornwall, they spent three years renovating a beautiful Georgian house by the sea, and then moved back to London, leaving a heavenly holiday rental, @pembrokelodge, behind them. "From the kitchen we can look out at the sea and see seals and boats bobbing around," says Bianca. "It’s beautiful even on a rainy day, with the water beating on the skylight. You feel that you’re outdoors, even when you’re not.” Follow the link in our story to see the rest of the interiors.
📸 @owengale

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by House & Garden Magazine in Bruern. May be an image of flower and nature.

node.text:
On the site of a former abbey in Oxfordshire, designer @angelcollinsgardens has combined ecclesiastical symmetry with informal planting to create a garden that is both awe-inspiring and delightfully domestic. The eighteenth-century house became a school in the latter half of the twentieth century, and were no records of the former garden, nor any archaeological clues in the landscape, so Angel was free to interpret the space as she thought best. Here mauve Verbena bonariensis contrasts with Rosa ‘Morning Mist’ below espaliered ‘Evereste’ crab apples in the parterre. Follow the link in our profile to read the full story.
📸@eva_nemeth

Angel Collins is a member of @thelistbyhouseandgarden

node.text:
In an extract from his book 'Notes on Decorating', American interior designer Markham Roberts recounts the story of his Pacific Northwest house, an old sea captain’s cottage on a cliff overlooking the shipping lanes of Puget Sound. This pale green room is the sun porch, well supplied with wicker furniture and the perfect place for sunset drinks. "It is lovely to watch the light fade over the water and mountains beyond as we play backgammon," says Markham. "The painted-wicker chaise at the end of the porch makes an ideal reading (mostly napping) spot." Follow the link in our profile to see the rest of the extract.
📸@nelson.hancock

node.text:
The owners of this rustic farmhouse in the backcountry of Ibiza have brought renewed vibrancy to its interiors. Bright constellations of unexpected secondhand objects and fabrics from around the world warm the inside of the house. Exposed wooden beams and fired earthen floors run throughout the house, as colourful rugs and fabrics from Europe and Africa brighten the spaces. Read the full story (an extract from @gestalten's new book 'Life's A Beach) on the link in our profile.
📸@gaelleleboulicautpics

node.text:
Interiors studio @arentpykestudio has anchored this Sydney Harbour newbuild firmly in the Australian vernacular with indigenous art, native hardwoods and a palette of outback-inspired tones, to create comfortable and compelling interiors. This sunken area – ‘the cosiest part of the house’ – has an eye-catching ‘Serie Up 2000’ armchair and footstool by @gaetano.pesce for @bebitalia and shelving by @vitsoe displaying books and glassware.

‘People often say the garden is very green: perhaps this is the Italian in me,' says hotel designer @olgapolizzi, who, despite living in Britain all her life, feels her Italian roots strongly. Her Sussex garden has a unique character, setting the formality of an Italian villa against the romance of an English flower garden. Follow the link in our profile to read more.

node.text:
Never one to rush things, @emmamilnewatson has gradually breathed new life into a centuries-old rectory in Sussex, respecting its history while creating a distinctive home for her family by effortlessly mixing classic and contemporary elements. Added to the back of the house a few years ago with the aim of 
making it appear more streamlined and symmetrical, this handsome veranda has a panelled ceiling and pillars in ‘Down Pipe’ by @farrowandball, providing a strong backdrop for cane furniture from @hadeda_co.

A wisteria-draped pergola covers a seating area in the garden at architect Mario Connio’s Andalusian farmhouse. Succumbing to love at first sight, he purchased the abandoned farm more than 40 years ago from an order of nuns and he has been developing and perfecting it ever since. node.text:
This Victorian house in north-west London has been gradually transformed with clever use of colour, natural textures and vintage pieces to showcase the distinctive style of its owner, interior designer Deniz Bayern of @studiokaya.  The first conundrum when she bought it was how to enlarge the ground floor without creating an open-plan layout. She opted to push out at the back by three metres and add bifold doors on two sides. ‘The design was inspired by Victorian glasshouses,’ Deniz says.
